Here is a comparison of how the codebase will look after removing the **Spring-style (annotation/scanner-based)** attributes and replacing them with an explicit, modern **Fluent C++ API style**.

---

### 1. Dependency Injection (DI) & Lifecycle Management

#### Before (Spring-style Annotations & Reflection Scanner)
The classes are annotated with custom attributes, and a build-time regex scanner auto-wires the constructors.
```cpp
// service/user_service.h
struct [[=novaboot::di::service{}]] UserService {
    UserRepository& user_repo;

    // Constructor injection is automatically wired by compiler reflection
    explicit UserService(UserRepository& repo) : user_repo(repo) {}

    [[=novaboot::di::post_construct{}]]
    void init() {
        spdlog::info("UserService initialized");
    }

    [[=novaboot::di::pre_destroy{}]]
    void cleanup() {
        spdlog::info("UserService shutting down");
    }
};

// main.cpp
RootContainer di_root;
novaboot_di_register_all(di_root); // Automatically generated list of components
di_root.build();
```

#### After (Fluent C++ Style)
Standard C++ classes without custom compiler-specific attributes. Dependencies and wiring logic are fully transparent and controlled directly in the composition root.
```cpp
// service/user_service.h
struct UserService {
    UserRepository& user_repo;

    explicit UserService(UserRepository& repo) : user_repo(repo) {}

    void init() {
        spdlog::info("UserService initialized");
    }

    void cleanup() {
        spdlog::info("UserService shutting down");
    }
};

// main.cpp
RootContainer di_root;

// Explicit, visible DI registration with lambda factory and fluent callbacks
di_root.singleton<UserService>([](auto& c) {
    return new UserService(c.template resolve<UserRepository>());
})
.on_start(&UserService::init)
.on_stop(&UserService::cleanup);

di_root.build();
```

